### TITLE ###
NestedFnDoesNotInheritOuterNarrowing
### DESCRIPTION ###
A nested function definition opens its own frame. Narrowings from
the surrounding scope don't leak in - the nested function can be
called from anywhere, so its body must reason from base types only.
### INPUT ###
fn outer(x: int?):
    if x != null:
        fn inner():
            y = x
        inner()
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  y @ 4:13 -> <no-type>
  x @ 4:17 -> int?
  inner @ 5:9 -> fn()

# Symbol types
  inner (fn): fn()
  outer (fn): fn(int?)
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
NestedFnDoesNotLeakBodyMutationsOut
### DESCRIPTION ###
Inside the nested fn body, reassignments update the local frame;
on return to the surrounding scope the outer frame must be intact.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x != null:
        fn g():
            x = null
            y = x
        after_inner = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  x @ 4:13 -> <no-type>
  y @ 5:13 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:17 -> dynamic
  after_inner @ 6:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 6:23 -> int

# Symbol types
  after_inner (local): int
  f (fn): fn(int?)
  g (fn): fn()
  x (local): dynamic
  x (param): int?
  y (local): dynamic

# Diagnostics
  (none)
